The FT-IR spectra of carbon dots exhibit peaks at 3420 and 3321 cm−1 assigned to the stretching vibrations of the O-H and N-H groups, respectively. The bands at 3321, 3112 & 3030 cm−1 reflect the presence of aromatic = CH groups and C-H alkyl stretching vibrations. The intense absorption peaks at 1720, 1495, 1450, 1378 & 1230 cm−1 can be attributed to the carbonyl stretching (C = O), C = C stretching (aromatic ring), C-N & C-O linkages (Fig. S2A) [41]. This shows that the surface states of the carbon dots are rich in amino & carboxyl functional groups. The FTIR spectrum of fibrous silica (DFNS) shows peaks at 3442, 1070, and 760 cm−1, matching the stretching & bending vibrations of Si-OH & Si-O-Si linkage. The covalent attachment of the thiol group can be confirmed by the presence of alkyl stretching vibration –CH & -SH around 2927, 2860 & 2265 cm−1 
                        [30,42,43]. Confirmation of successful loading of carbon dots into DFNS@SH is evidenced by preserving all carbon dot peaks in the final material CD@DFNS@SH, with the silica framework remaining intact (Fig. 4
                        ).
